author: @hadjerouali7336
text: -- TEMP TABLE  IF OBJECT_ID('tempdb..#PercentPopulationVaccinated') IS NOT NULL drop table if exists #PercentPopulationVaccinated; create table #PercentPopulationVaccinated ( continent nvarchar(255), Location nvarchar(255),  Date datetime, Population numeric, New_vaccinations numeric, RollingPeopleVaccinated numeric  )  insert into #PercentPopulationVaccinated select     dea.continent,     dea.location, dea.date,     CASE          WHEN ISNUMERIC(dea.population) = 1 THEN CAST(dea.population AS NUMERIC)          ELSE NULL      END AS Population,     CASE          WHEN ISNUMERIC(vac.new_vaccinations) = 1 THEN CAST(vac.new_vaccinations AS NUMERIC)          ELSE NULL      END AS New_vaccinations,  SUM(CASE          WHEN ISNUMERIC(vac.new_vaccinations) = 1 THEN CAST(vac.new_vaccinations AS NUMERIC)          ELSE 0      END) OVER (PARTITION BY dea.location ORDER BY dea.location, dea.date) AS RollingPeopleVaccinated --(RollingPeopleVaccinated/population) * 100 -- ou bien  sum(convert(int, vac.new_vaccinations)) over (partition by dea.location)  From [Portfolio SQL Prodjects]..CovidDeaths dea join [dbo].[Covid Vaccination] vac  on dea.location = vac.location and dea.date = vac.date where dea.continent is not null  --order by 2,3 select *, (RollingPeopleVaccinated/population) * 100  from #PercentPopulationVaccinated   Explanation:  Numeric Validation: The script uses the ISNUMERIC function to check if the values in dea.population and vac.new_vaccinations are numeric before attempting to cast them. Conditional Casting: If the values are numeric, they are cast to NUMERIC. If not, they are set to NULL or 0 as appropriate. Population Filter: The final SELECT statement includes a filter to exclude rows where Population is NULL, ensuring that the percentage calculation only includes valid data. This should resolve the conversion error. If the ISNUMERIC function is not sufficient for your needs (as it sometimes considers certain non-numeric characters like currency symbols as numeric), you might need to use a more robust validation method.

text: For anyone having issues importing data into MySQL here are the steps I took:   1. I imported the data as an CSV file. author: @mahhingaminggate5028
text: It took me an hour and a half to complete the first 15 minutes. So, the import-export wizard was not working from the Windows search; it was giving a big error (that was related to SQL Express version), and the inbuilt option was also giving that error of 32-64 bit thing. How I was able to fix it was by downloading the "32-bit Microsoft Access Database Engine 2016 Redistributable" and running it from the command prompt. After that, I was able to import directly from SSMS.  Moreover, in the destination, instead of the native client, I chose the last option, Microsoft OLE DB Provider.  Hope that helped a little .

text: I realized that while I was importing the dataset into mysql workbench, some of those data were truncated. If you encountered same issue, all you need to do is change all blank cells to 'NULL'. author: @cn4813
text: Around 59:00 I was getting this error: ORDER BY list of RANGE window frame cannot contain expressions of LOB type.  My location in my CovidDeaths was listed as a nvarchar(MAX).  I changed to a nvarchar(255) within the script.  This is what I did to help in this area.  Hope this helps anyone that may have ran into the same issue.  SELECT DEA.continent, DEA.location, DEA.date, DEA.population, VAC.new_vaccinations, 	SUM(vac.new_vaccinations) over (Partition By DEA.location ORDER BY CONVERT(nvarchar(255), DEA.location), DEA.date) AS VaccinationsPerDay FROM [Portfolio Project]..CovidDeaths as DEA JOIN [Portfolio Project]..CovidVaccinations as VAC 	ON DEA.location = VAC.location 	AND DEA.date = VAC.date WHERE DEA.continent is not null ORDER BY 2, 3

author: @SumanSingh-mn3hq
text: if anyone getting errors in 29:00 here's the code: SELECT   location,   MAX(total_cases) as Highest_infectioncount,   population,   CASE      WHEN MAX(total_cases) = 0 THEN NULL     ELSE (CAST(MAX(total_cases) AS float) / population) * 100   END AS InfectedpopulationPercentage FROM PortfolioProject..['covid deaths$'] GROUP BY location, population ORDER BY InfectedpopulationPercentage

text: so i am using SMSS 2022 and the import/export feature still stinks.   I was able to use *[ Tasks > Import Data... ]* to import the 97-03 format of the dataset. The only downside is that I had to assign data types to each column and allow for NULL values by manually checking boxes. In any case i will make sure to have all data in CSV format whenever I need to import data. text: CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE PercentPopulationVaccinated (     continent VARCHAR(255),     location VARCHAR(255),     date DATE,     population NUMERIC,     new_vaccinations NUMERIC,     RollingPeopleVaccinated NUMERIC );  -- Insert data into the temporary table INSERT INTO PercentPopulationVaccinated SELECT     dea.continent,     dea.location,     dea.date,     dea.population,     vacc.new_vaccinations,     SUM(CAST(vacc.new_vaccinations AS SIGNED)) OVER (PARTITION BY dea.location ORDER BY dea.location, dea.date) AS RollingPeopleVaccinated FROM Project1.coviddeaths dea JOIN Project1.covidvacc vacc ON dea.location = vacc.location AND dea.date = vacc.date;  -- Retrieve data from the temporary table and calculate the percentage SELECT *,        (RollingPeopleVaccinated / population) * 100 AS PercentPopulationVaccinated FROM PercentPopulationVaccinated;  aint working in MYSQL workbench ladddsss any help will be appreciated

author: @user-hn5pd3tx5s
text: For those who are stuck at 1:01:49 while running the query -- Looking at total population Vs Vaccinations SELECT d.continent, d.location, d.date, d.population, NULLIF(CONVERT(float, v.new_vaccinations), 0) AS new_vaccinations, 		SUM(NULLIF(CONVERT(float, v.new_vaccinations), 0)) OVER (Partition by d.location ORDER BY d.location, d.date) AS RollingPeopleVaccinated FROM CovidDeaths d JOIN CovidVaccinations v 	ON d.location = v.location AND d.date = v.date WHERE d.continent IS NOT NULL ORDER BY 2,3

author: @user-kq3tc5tu1c
text: Greetings Again Alex.  Just finished working through this awesome video again.  Learned a lot, AGAIN!  Your presentation was fine, no issues at all.  On my side, I had to work through technology issues related to running an SQL product on my M1 MacBook Pro.  Not as straight forward as one might hope.  I discovered (AGAIN) that trying to run MSSQLSVR on a Parallels VM just never quite worked right.  I could load various versions, then something just would behave - DOH!  Then, I went back to PostgreSQL and pgAdmin 4.  Everything worked okay until a recent pgAdmin 4 upgrade started crashing.  DOH!  After this, I went back to my tried and true Docker/Azure Data Studio tools.  I was able to do everything in your video with a few minor tweaks here and there.  For example, (in my experience) Azure Data Studio won't import an Excel doc like your SQLSVR did, so I imported everything as CSV flat files and got to do WAY more CAST-ing than in your video!  I suppose my most important takeaway is that one should either buy the right computer OR pick one RDBMS and stick with it.  Too many squirrels can  be a HUGE distraction.  'Nuf said and Thanks again for all of the work you've done producing these videos for anyone who want's to learn.  Cheers!

author: @MohamedAhmed-bw8bm
text: *guys, does anyone have any idea why this works just fine* WITH CountryInfo(Location, population, total_cases, InfectionPercentage, TotalDeathCount) AS (     SELECT Location, population, SUM(new_cases) AS total_cases,            ROUND((MAX(CONVERT(Total_deaths, SIGNED))/ population) * 100, 2) AS InfectionPercentage,            MAX(CONVERT(Total_deaths, SIGNED)) AS TotalDeathCount     FROM CovidDeaths     WHERE continent IS NOT NULL     GROUP BY Location, population ) SELECT *, ROUND((TotalDeathCount/total_cases)*100, 2) AS PercentageOfDeath,        (total_cases - TotalDeathCount) AS Recovered,        ROUND(((total_cases - TotalDeathCount) / total_cases) * 100, 2) AS PercentageOfRecovery FROM CountryInfo ORDER BY InfectionPercentage DESC;  *but here  InfectionPercentage is always 0*  -- Create a temporary table CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE IF NOT EXISTS CountryInfoTemp (   Location NVARCHAR(255),   Population NUMERIC,   TotalCases NUMERIC,   InfectionPercentage NUMERIC,   TotalDeathCount NUMERIC );  -- Insert data into the temporary table INSERT INTO CountryInfoTemp SELECT Location, population, SUM(new_cases) AS total_cases,        ROUND((MAX(Total_deaths)/ population) * 100, 2) AS InfectionPercentage,        MAX(Total_deaths) AS TotalDeathCount FROM CovidDeaths WHERE continent IS NOT NULL GROUP BY Location, population;  -- Retrieve data from the temporary table SELECT *,        ROUND((TotalDeathCount/TotalCases)*100, 2) AS PercentageOfDeath,        CAST(((TotalCases - TotalDeathCount) / TotalCases) * 100 AS DECIMAL(10, 2)) AS PercentageOfRecovery FROM CountryInfoTemp ORDER BY InfectionPercentage DESC;

text: Oof, I spent 3 hours trying to get the data imported.  The Excel/SQL Server route didn't work.  I went down the SSMS/Flat File rabbit hole and found out that there is a row at the end of the data that contains the column names, yeah, so row 1 repeats at row 31,0000 something.  So the [date] column, for example, won't reconcile as a date value because the last item in the data is an unconvertable string value of "date".  Once I deleted that row from the CSV I was finally able to get the data imported.  Ugh, I need some ice cream or something. ;)

author: @vanct02
text: From what I have followed so far, if you do this project in 2023, be careful of some queries. First thing I noticed is that the total_cases is cumulative and it only increases. This means it does not accurately reflect the current number of covid cases for the country and if you do a simple division of total_cases/population, this does not reflect the infected rate. Some countries will give you 50%-70% infected rate, which is crazy, and it is totally wrong if you interpreted it as 50% of the population got COVID. So watch with caution. At this point I think this project has become far less relevant.

author: @jacobmckenna2468
text: Hello! Thank you so much for all of the free resources you put on this channel! I am currently going through this project and wanted to offer a solution to the whole continent count error if anyone is doing this right now.   I was able to get the correct count by continent by utilizing a subquery. This is what it looks like. Hope this helps!  SELECT	location, 		Max(cast(total_deaths as BigInt)) as total_death_count FROM	ProjectPortfolio..CovidDeaths WHERE	continent is null 		AND 		location in (SELECT DISTINCT continent 					FROM ProjectPortfolio..CovidDeaths 					WHERE continent is not null) GROUP BY location ORDER BY total_death_count DESC

author: @snowholt
text: Great tutorial, Thanks for the free courses. However, you need to update the video for new SSMS and SQL2022 because The SQL Server Native Client (often abbreviated SNAC) has been removed from SQL Server 2022 (16.x) and SQL Server Management Studio 19 (SSMS). The SQL Server Native Client (SQLNCLI or SQLNCLI11) and the legacy Microsoft OLE DB Provider for SQL Server (SQLOLEDB) are not recommended for new application development. Switch to the new Microsoft OLE DB Driver (MSOLEDBSQL) for SQL Server or the latest Microsoft ODBC Driver for SQL Server going forward. :)

author: @Tabi22
text: If you are getting the "Msg 8134, Level 16, State 1, Line 35 Divide by zero error encountered." Error or anything similar with "Divide by zero error" the reason for this is because your denominator is 0. To prevent this from happening you need to alter the script Alex has provided:  SELECT location, date, total_cases, total_deaths, (total_deaths/NULLIF(total_cases, 0)*100) AS Death_Percentage FROM PortfolioProject..CovidDeaths  The NULLIF script is as follows:  NULLIF(expression1, expression2)  Two expressions are required in a NULLIF() function. The function checks to see if both expressions are the same. If they are, then the result will equal null. An example is NULLIF('Hello', 'Hello') will result in "NULL" because Hello and Hello are the same, but if they differ it will return the first expression (i.e. NULLIF('Hello', 'world') will return "Hello" once executed because Hello does not equal world). In this case NULLIF(total_cases, 0), if your total cases equal zero, it will result in a null and will null out your Death_Percentage equation because you cannot divide by 0. If your denominator is NOT 0 and it is a value it will use the total_cases value and complete the percentage equation to give you the Death_Percentage.

text: Also: total_cases and death_cases are not int format when they are loaded so its showing fault. This is how to fix it: -- Alter the table to convert the columns to int format ALTER TABLE covid_deaths ALTER COLUMN total_cases INT;  ALTER TABLE covid_deaths ALTER COLUMN total_deaths INT;  -- Update the table to cast the existing data to int format UPDATE covid_deaths SET total_cases = CAST(total_cases AS INT),     total_deaths = CAST(total_deaths AS INT);  -- Verify the changes SELECT TOP 10 total_cases, total_deaths FROM covid_deaths;   --calculate % per country/ states SELECT location, date, total_cases, total_deaths,         CAST((total_deaths*100.0/NULLIF(total_cases, 0)) AS FLOAT) AS DeathPercentage FROM covid_deaths where location like '%states%' order by 1,2  --calculate % per country SELECT location, date, total_cases, total_deaths,         CAST((total_deaths*100.0/NULLIF(total_cases, 0)) AS FLOAT) AS DeathPercentage FROM covid_deaths order by 1,2

author: @o0tonmoy0o
text: Not sure if anyone else has come across issues while importing data to SSMS through Import Export Wizard (64-bit), but a few I have came across and the solutions I found are:   - SQL Server Import Export will not start as it is missing SSIS (SQL Server Integration Service) which is offered through the Developer instead of Express, so I tried installing Developer but then encountered another issue where it will not install Database Engine. So I Installed Express and only installed the Integrated Services through the Developer server.  - If you get an error during selected the table during the import wizard, try installing SQL Server 2012 Native Client, this fixed it for me.   Hope this helps someone, and if you have an easier solution, please let me know as I have done countless install/re-installs of SQL servers trying to find a solution lol

author: @naymulhulk840
text: # HELP 1  For people who are having problems with creating a database after successfully downloading and installing MS SQL SMS, please try using the following steps:  1. Figure out your computer name from windows my computer - > properties. COPY IT EXACTLY 2. To the copied name, add "\SQLEXPRESS" without the quotation marks 3. Before you click on connect, select options on the "Connect to Server"dialogue box that pops up when you open MS SQL SMS 4. Click on connection properties 5. Check Trust Server Certificate(if you do not do this your connection with be established, but TLS/SLS certificate wont be verified- very advanced stuff Google SLS/TLS certification to learn more)  Hope this helps

text: It took forever, but i finally figured out how to import the covid files. Save files in excel as CSV, right click your portfolio database, click task, import data. The the import wizard pops up, on the top where is says data source choose at Flat File Source, then browse for you file (make sure you select all files on the bottom right, so your CSV files can be seen),  then click next, click next again, under destination choose Microsoft OLE DB Provider for SQL Server, confirm the server name is correct, click next, click your file name if it's not already, then next, run immediately should already be checked, click next then finish. When the execution is successul, hit close.

author: @davidlisle3820
text: Just coming here to say that around the 9:30 mark you had the import destination as SQL Server Native Client 11.0, but that didn't work for me... Took me 3 hours to figure out that I was supposed to select Microsoft OLE DB Driver for SQL Server now. Found a note on the Microsoft website, which I pasted below. Just wanting to share this in case other people have the same problem. Your videos are great by the way, you explain things very well and it's easy to learn.  ---------------- The SQL Server Native Client (often abbreviated SNAC) has been removed from SQL Server 2022 (16.x) and SQL Server Management Studio 19 (SSMS). The SQL Server Native Client (SQLNCLI or SQLNCLI11) and the legacy Microsoft OLE DB Provider for SQL Server (SQLOLEDB) are not recommended for new application development. Switch to the new Microsoft OLE DB Driver (MSOLEDBSQL) for SQL Server or the latest Microsoft ODBC Driver for SQL Server going forward. For SQLNCLI that ships as a component of SQL Server Database engine (versions 2012 through 2019), see this Support Lifecycle exception.

author: @MewGulf13
text: Hopefully this helps someone:  I kept getting the  'Microsoft.ACE.OLEDB.12.0' or  'Microsoft.ACE.OLEDB.16.0' error and after days of searching, figured out it was incompatibility issues with my Microsoft Office x64 bit version and the SMSS Import/Export Wizard (through the application) which is a x32 bit.  I had to uninstall Office and its features (Excel, Word, etc) then re-download the x32 bit version, which finally got me through to the next stage, which another situation occurred when I couldn't find the 'SQL Server Native Client 11.0'  That server as been removed in the 22 version of SMSS, so Microsoft recommends the "Microsoft OLE DB Driver for SQL Server", which I  changed the Properties of: "Windows Authentication" as info to log on to the server and the database I want the file to be inserted into (aka PortfolioProject, in our case) You can test the connection, at the bottom, which will let you know if the test connection succeeded or not.  Good luck and best wishes on your career

author: @RoshanBholah
text: For anyone using Azure Data Studio and having trouble importing the CSV files with the SQL Import extension. You will need to change around with the Data Types that Azure identifies. e.g. change Small Int to Int or nvarchar(1) to nvarchar(50). In addition, I made all columns to allow null values. Making these corrections then worked and both CSV files imported into my database.

author: @cindaz8569
text: A few issues I ran into when trying to go through the bootcamp and the solutions I found: 1. Excel. I don't own a copy of Excel so I downloaded the Excel files from GitHub and opened them in Google Sheets. I made the edits to create the two different Excel files. I then downloaded them from Google Sheets as Excel files (.xlsx). 2. I was unable to upload the Excel files into my SQLExpress server with either the 32 or 64 bit processes mentioned in the video. I got one error about "provider is not registered on the local machine" and another that said "The system cannot find the file specified." After some Googling, it looks like it's just not an option for Express. I did two things which made it work for me: - I downloaded a free SQL Developer server instead of the Express one. It's shown in Alex's first SQL tutorial video. - I downloaded SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS) After I did these steps, I was able to upload the Excel file by right clicking it in the Object Explorer window > Tasks > Import Data... I didn't test if it worked through the 64 bit method shown in the video.  3. When choosing a destination for the Excel during the upload to SQL, I didn't have the "SQL Server Native Client 11" option shown in the video in my list or anything close to it. I selected "Microsoft OLE DB Provider for SQL Server" instead and it worked for me.  With these 3 solutions, I was able to follow along and perform all of the steps outlined in the video. Hope this helps!

author: @anhu9057
text: 38:57 I think it may be because it only showed the MAX value of total death count with the same continent no matter the locations, but actually what we are looking for is the SUM of the MAX value from the different locations with the same continent. I don't know the simplest way to solve it but I tried CTE and it worked.  WITH CTE_CovidDeath AS (SELECT location, continent, MAX(total_deaths) AS TotalDeathCount FROM `CovidAnalytics.CovidDeath` WHERE continent is not null -- to exclude location like 'world' or 'Asia' GROUP BY location, continent ) SELECT continent, SUM(CTE_CovidDeath.TotalDeathCount) AS TotalDeathCountPerContinent FROM CTE_CovidDeath GROUP BY continent ORDER BY TotalDeathCountPerContinent DESC

author: @pytorai8162
text: Here is my take on the ranking on the total number of deaths.  Hence, Ranking by max Total deaths. US is number 1 and China with 1.3 bil population is 89th and India is 3rd. So, is China's number under reported? or it is closer to the truth with 5226 reported deaths up to October 17th, 22.   with t2 as ( Select t1.location,  	   t1.max_tc,  	   t1.continent, ROW_NUMBER() Over(Order By t1.max_tc DESC) rn From	( 		Select location, continent, Max(total_deaths) max_tc From dbo.CovidDeaths Group By location, continent 		) t1 Where t1.continent not like '%grouped%' 		) Select * From t2 Where location like '%aus%'

author: @tuanhuypham9291
text: I completed this project today and an issue I ran into in SQL Server was hot being able to filter out rows in the continent column based on null values. It turns out that there are blank spaces in the column instead of null values, and you can use   UPDATE database..table SET continent = NULLIF(continent, ' ')  to update the table so you can run the query as-is. Hope this helps!

text: Alex the analyst. Thank you for the lesson. Here is a code to get the maximum total deaths per a given date grouped  by continent.  Select continent, location, date, total_deaths From  ( 	Select continent,  		location, 		total_deaths, 		date, 		ROW_NUMBER() Over(partition by continent order by total_deaths DESC) as rowNumber  	From CovidDeaths 		Where continent in ('Oceania', 'Europe', 'North America', 'South America', 'Africa')  		and date = '2021-10-17' ) as gtable Where rowNumber = 1

author: @poke5443
text: I had an issue with nvarchar: All columns were imported as nvarchar instead of a float. I figured out that the issue was from the way execl formated my data. Perviously, execl was taking a comma as a decimal delimiter, however, the data input used the period as a decimal delimiter. you can easily change that in the settings on excel. Select all numerical columns one by one, then click on "Text to columns" then click Finish.

text: As of September of 2022 the data has separated the locations by income as well and continents. author: @lindseylowry2594
text: First, Alex, you beautiful life saver of a man. I want to kiss your bald head and cry from gratitude because of this. If anyone else is having a tough time with the CTE table using BigQuery, here's the syntax:  -- Using CTE to perform Calculation on Partition By in Previous Query  With PopVsVac  as  ( Select dea.continent, dea.location, dea.date, dea.population, vac.new_vaccinations, SUM(CAST(vac.new_vaccinations as int)) OVER (PARTITION BY dea.location ORDER BY dea.location, dea.date) as rolling_people_vaccinated FROM `portfolioproject-360018.Covid.CovidDeaths` dea JOIN `portfolioproject-360018.Covid.CovidVaccinations` vac   on dea.location = vac.location    and dea.date = vac.date  Where dea.continent is not null )  Select *, (rolling_people_vaccinated/Population)*100 as vaccinated_country_population From PopVsVac

text: 38:23 The reason we are not getting correct total deaths when we break down by continents is that in our query we are using MAX(cast(total_deaths as int)), so what it does is it returns the maximum total_death from that particular continent(ex in Oceania continent it returned 910, which is the total death count for Australia and highest in its continent). We need to replace the query by- select continent,  sum(new_deaths) from coviddeaths where continent!='' group by continent; Hope this helps!

author: @tatianapushkarskaia7505
text: Thank you for the tutorial, it was a really nice experience. As some in the comments, I run into a couple of errors too, but immediately found solution in the comments or on Stack Overflow.  ❗Error: ORDER BY list of RANGE window frame has total size of 1020 bytes. Largest size supported is 900 bytes. 📗Most likely you didn't want a RANGE UNBOUNDED PRECEDING window frame anyway, but unfortunately that is the default. Instead, use ROWS UNBOUNDED PRECEDING: SUM(CONVERT(bigint,vac.new_vaccinations)) OVER (Partition by dea.location Order by dea.location, dea.date ROWS UNBOUNDED PRECEDING) as RollingPeopleVaccinated  ❗Error: Couldn't see the created view after refreshing 📗Check with  Select * From dbo.PercentPopulationVaccinated if it exists. If it exists, so it's just MS SQL giving us trouble 😅  I saved quarries as the SQL file, then closed out of MS SQL, reopened MS SQL and opened the saved SQL file, deleted the Create View statement, retyped the statement, executed the query, refreshed the views folder, and it worked.🤯(How Alex said, "Don't ask me why")   @Alex, also thank you for encouraging speech at the end, it means a lot  ❤️

author: @klaubbs7839
text: I had an error that someone else posted on StackOverflow so I figured I would share how I overcame it. When creating the view you get the correct message that the command was completed. If you refresh the view isn't there. You reexecute the command and it says that object already exists but you can't find the view. I saved the file, closed out of SSMS, and reopened the file in SSMS, then I deleted the Create View statement, retyped it, executed the command, refreshed the views file and it worked. I hoped this helped somebody!

text: @ 33:00 when you say the data type for the columns is wrong, it most likely happened when you imported the data. When I got the csv file from ourworldwithdata and worked it in Excel, some rows were not converted to numeric type because they had a period separating decimals. author: @clyde1817
text: Hi alex! i did the total deaths and cases for global ones differently as i think you got the max death and case grouped by the continent not total. i used this query for anyone who wants to check.  CREATE VIEW [deathpercont2] AS Select location, max(cast(total_deaths as bigint)) as TotalDeathCount,max(total_cases) as total_cases From [Portfolio project]..[Covid deaths] --Where location like '%states%' Where continent is null  and location not in ('World', 'European Union', 'International','Upper middle income','High income','Lower middle income','Low income') Group by location   SELECT sum(total_cases) as total_cases_world,sum(totaldeathcount) as total_deaths_world,sum(totaldeathcount)/sum(total_cases)*100 as deathspercase FROM deathpercont2

author: @ninjapaperhuman
text: For those having problems importing to MySQL on a Mac, this is what I did:  1. Edit on excel (make sure date is in the right format) and save as CSV. 2. Double check if your date is in the right format by opening the csv file in a text editor. DO NOT open in excel again it will change the format automatically. 3. After you make a database in MySQL, right click on 'tables' under your chosen database and click 'Table Data Import Wizard' 4. Choose the csv file that you saved before, and transfer to the database.

author: @ck6cj6d93
text: February 2022. Stucked on importing the excel data. Tried changing it to .xls but had "NULL" values for the majority of the data. Plus when I downloaded the SSMS, it only has 64 bits importer, and I couldn't find how to install the 32 bits anywhere on the internet.   Fix:  1. save your excel sheets into CSV format. 2. right-click on your project database -> tasks -> import data -> data source (select "flat data source") -> browse file location (*remeber to select  to show .csv file type) -> SQL client 11.0 -> done  Spent hours trying to figure this out, hopefully, this helps and can save yall some time.

author: @marcusbelanger3489
text: If you are encountering an error that says: "ORDER BY list of RANGE window frame has total size of 1020 bytes. Largest size supported is 900 bytes."  this is caused by the "cd.date" following the ORDER BY statement. I don't understand why this is happening (I believe it has something to do with the column data type),  but to fix it you simply adjust the "cd.date" to "CONVERT(date, cd.date). Your final query should look similar to:  SELECT cd.continent, cd.location, cd.date, cd.population, cv.new_vaccinations,  SUM(CONVERT(bigint, cv.new_vaccinations))  OVER (Partition by cd.location ORDER BY cd.location, CONVERT(date, cd.date)) AS cumulative_vaccinations  FROM CovidDeaths cd JOIN CovidVaccinations cv ON cd.location = cv.location AND cd.date = cv.date WHERE cd.continent is not null  --AND cd.location like '%states%' ORDER BY 2,3  ;

text: For the CTE part where Alex explains...I think there is some misunderstanding... To get the 'percentage population vaccinated',  1. USE 'people_fully_vaccinated' column from covid_vaccinations 2. I don't think you need to use CTE to get the 'percentage population vaccinated' 3. Just do (vac.people_fully_vaccinated/population)*100   For better understanding, I wrote the detailed explanation of the columns in [covid_vaccinations] table - <total_vaccination>: literally the total of every single vaccination 'SHOT' - <people_vaccinated> : only includes people who got their "FIRST" vaccination shot -- <people_fully_vaccinated>: people who got 'BOTH' of vaccination shots -- <total_booster>: people who got "MORE" than two vaccination shots -- <new_vaccinations> : this column only exists when there are all the records of <people_vaccinated>, <people_fully_vaccinated>, <total_booster> columns more than two days in a row. It simply explains additional shots that are used in the certain date. And it adds up to <total_vaccination>.  Please let me know if I misunderstood the columns or if there is anyone with different idea!  Thank you again Alex for the great video!!

author: @scottterry3235
text: This is so cool! You are so helpful with my goal goal of learning SQL to go beyond what I have previously done with Excel and proprietary databases! I can't wait to see what else we are going to learn!  At 33 minutes we just hit the snag of having incorrect types for number fields, which I ran into a lot with importing data files. The issue is that import wizards only check the first few lines of data, and usually if they don't find any data they just assign a "catch-all" data type like VARCHAR. To help the wizards know what to do I either a) move a line up to the first line that has representative data in every field , b) re-sort the data so that this occurs, or c) add a dummy first line of data that I can then delete after import. Since these files were sorted by date and had a ton of blanks, I opted for dummy data and it worked great.

text: Dont feel like skimming other comments right now but if you get this error...  Arithmetic overflow error converting expression to data type int. Warning: Null value is eliminated by an aggregate or other SET operation.  Change it from int to bigint  Select dea.continent, dea.location, dea.date, dea.population, vac.new_vaccinations , SUM(CONVERT(bigint,vac.new_vaccinations)) OVER (Partition by dea.location) From PortfolioProject..CovidDeaths dea Join PortfolioProject..CovidVaccinations vac 	On dea.location = vac.location 	and dea.date = vac.date where dea.continent is not null order By 2,3  FJB

author: @asr2021
text: Regarding the query at this timestamp 25:50 SELECT Location, date, total_cases, population, (total_cases/population)*100   FROM portfolioproject.coviddeaths WHERE location like %states% ORDER BY 1,2;   Please keep in mind that this calculation will not give you the total number of unique people who contracted the virus in the U.S. i.e If the same person contracted the virus, say 3 separate times, over the past year, all 3 of those instances would be counted in 'total_cases'

text: Hello Alex and everyone, I wrote the following query  mentioned at 59:45 :   --Looking at the Total Population and Vaccinations   Select dea.continent,dea.location, dea.date, dea.population, vac.new_vaccinations,  SUM(CAST(vac.new_vaccinations as bigint)) OVER (Partition By dea.location Order by dea.location,dea.date) as RollingPeopleVaccinated  From PortfolioProject..['covid-deaths$'] dea Join PortfolioProject..['covid-vaccinations$'] vac  on dea.location = vac.location  and dea.date = vac.date    where dea.continent is not null   order by 2,3  However each date is repeating 10 times before we move on to the next date. For Eg:  For location Albania, the date 13/01/2021 is repeating 10 times taking the total vaccinations to 600 instead of 60.  It would be great if you guys could help me out on this issue.

author: @rogermean
text: On the CTE query near the end, I get the following error 'ORDER BY list of RANGE window frame has total size of 1020 bytes. Largest size supported is 900 bytes.'  EDIT: This error is because of the date field. You need to do cast(deaths'dot'date as nvarchar(128)) . (don't actually write 'dot', I just put that in text to spot youtube linking it) The 128 isn't specific, it just needs to be low enough to not exceed the byte limit.

text: Hi Alex. I came up with this script for getting the max_total_ deaths per continent. author: @Gunflame69
text: @Alex the Analyst, I love your channel.  I have been working with data for 16 years... but usually from the business side, and let the "technical people" develop the tools while I do all the requirements, mappings, validation, cleansing, testing and etc.. I have been putting away learning SQL for a long long time. I only have written minor VBA/excel codes for work, though I can read and understand most of written code I see.  I finally feel like I'm learning SQL. So thank you very much  38:10 for those trying to figure out a different way to get max cases per continent. I went with a subquery  Select Table2.continent, sum(Table2.MaxDeathsLoc) as TotalDeaths  from  	(Select Continent, Location, max(cast(total_deaths as int)) MaxDeathsLoc 	from [PortfolioProject-1]..covidDeaths 	Where continent is not null 	Group by continent, location 	--order by 3 desc 	) as Table2 Group by continent  I also learned that you can't use "order by" inside a subquery.  So I commented it out.

author: @0x007A
text: I realize you wanted to start with a "simple" workflow to import data from Microsoft Excel into Microsoft SQL Server, but wouldn't importing the entire original spreadsheet into the database and subsequently extracting the desired fields into two separate tables been only marginally "more complex?" Unfortunately, some people watching this video will get the impression that the manual process you demonstrate is an acceptable practice.  1. Import the original data using the build-in menu options 2. Create the two target tables 3a. Select desired fields from source_table_name and insert into table_1 3b. Select desired fields from source_table_name and insert into table_2 4. Proceed as you demonstrate in the video  You mention the purpose is to demonstrate skills to potential employers, so the manual subdivision of the origainal data file might be viewed negatively by some employers viewing this portfiolio project. Otherwise, this is a very good introduction for beginners.

author: @amystucker4282
text: I'm transitioning from teaching to data analytics. I recently finished the Google Data Analytics Certification, and I've been struggling to figure out how to get my portfolio started. I found this video, and I got really excited to use this as a guided project. Then, I saw Alex was using Covid data, and I had to pause to consider if I could handle it. I lost my dad to Covid 4 months ago. This is personal.  However, I think I need this now as another way to process through the continuing grief. The fact is, data is personal. Each of these data points describes people. Someone's father, mother, sister, brother, grandparent, friend, and so on. This data is reality, and it's so important to analyze it in order to truly show the impact that this pandemic has made. Especially, as things may be getting back to "normal" in some places around the world, this data proves that "normal" is not the same without the lives of so many. And maybe, just maybe, analysis and visualization of this dataset can encourage others to get the vaccine, and we can be more informed moving forward.
